feed.title: Brisbane Ranges - Moths
feed.subtitle: The Brisbane Ranges has a biodiverse moth fauna. Many detected species have yet to be identified. This collection is an attempt to offer identification features, in photos and tags, that may assist others observing moths in the Brisbane Ranges to apply correct species identification to their observations.

entry.title: Anthela repleta
entry.content: In photo 2, the moth has laid eggs on the stem of Pultenaea gunnii subsp. tuberculata.

entry.title: Anestia ombrophanes
entry.content: This is a lighter colour form - can be variable.

entry.title: Metrocampa biplaga
entry.content: This moth has been reclassified to (Azelina) biplaga

entry.title: Arhodia lasiocamparia
entry.content: Top photo is the female, lower photo is the male.

entry.title: Opsirhina lechriodes
entry.content: Both are same species: one injured with no wing spot on left side and no 'snout'.

entry.title: Sinpunctiptilia emissalis
entry.content: Also known as Platyptilia emissalis. Feeds on Digger's Speedwell (Derwentia perfoliata).

entry.title: Alucita phricodes
entry.content: Unmistakable - has both fore and hindwings wings deeply cleft into numerous narrow lobes. This one was about 1.8cm from wing tip to wing tip.

entry.title: Phrataria transcissata
entry.content: This moth is particularly difficult to photograph because it rarely sits with its wings open.

entry.title: Palleopa innotata
entry.content: Male and female of the species

entry.title: Epicyme rubropunctaria
entry.content: Geometridae spp. Possibly Idaea or Scopula spp.

entry.title: Mimaglossa nauplialis
entry.content: Pyralidae spp. Identification thanks to Darren Carman.

entry.title: Cosmodes elegans
entry.content: A rare pale-brown morph of this species.

entry.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
entry.content: A species of Epicoma. There were also multiple clusters of eggs on the glass of the windows around the house. They were covered in hair the same colour as the abdominal tuft of the moth.
